ish museumperhaps because his mother was already showing signs of the mental disturbance for which she was admitted first to st luke’s hospital for lunaticks in old street in  and then bethlem hospital in  turner was sent to stay with uncles at brentford in  and sunningwell in  and to margate in  where he also attended school at home his father encouraged his artistic talent and showed off his drawings in his shop in december  after a term’s probation turner entered the royal academy schools where he progressed from the plaister academy drawing from casts of ancient sculpture to the life class in  he augmented his studies with other work experience with architects and architectural draughtsman including thomas malton whom he later described as ‘my real master’ and painting scenery for the london stage – the origin presumably of a lifelong love of music and opera by  with his friend thomas girtin he attended the evening ‘academy’ hosted by dr thomas monro at his house in the adelphi copying works by other artists a specialist in mental illness monro would later be responsible for his mother’s care at bethlemjoseph mallord william turner –view in the avon gorge pen and ink and watercolour on papersupport  x  mmtate daccepted by the nation as part of the turner bequest dfigjoseph mallord william turnerview in the avon gorge tate dturner’s varied activities indicate wide interests as well as a need to fund his academy education the flourishing market for landscape and antiquarian topography whether watercolours for exhibition and sale or reproduction in prints and books provided his first real income early trips outside london including a visit to friends of his father’s at bristol in  alerted him to the value of sketching on the spot as the basis of studio and commercial work he seems to have thought of having his views of the avon gorge – which won him the nickname ‘prince of the rocks’ – published as prints fig from the mids he settled on the routine he maintained for much of his life touring in summer and working in the studio in the winter months for the following year’s exhibitions on commissions or for the engraver the first engravings after his topographical drawings appeared in the copperplate magazine – and the pocket magazine – postrevolutionary wars in europe confined his first tours to home ground the midlands in  the north in  and wales on several occasions up to  in  he visited scotlandturner exhibited at the royal academy from  showing watercolours until  when he sent his first oil fishermen at sea tate t fig its marine subject signalling wider ambitions as a painter and his refusal to be typecast as a topographer in the following years his exhibited works diversified into history literature and myth challenged the styles of the old masters and made rapid advances in technique while some of his first important commissions were for architectural and topographical watercolours such as views of salisbury and its cathedral and his country estate stourhead ordered by richard colt hoare in  prominent patrons soon supported his wider endeavours william beckford commissioned views of his new gothic palace fonthill but also bought turner’s first history painting the fifth plague of egypt indianapolis museum of art an essay in the manner of the french painter nicolas poussin in  the same year the duke of bridgewater commissioned dutch boats in a gale private collection as a companion for his rising gale by willem van de velde the younger toledo museum of art ohio in  during the peace of amiens a consortium of noblemen sponsored a visit to paris enabling turner to study the old masters in the louvre and a tour of the swiss alps newbey lowson a gentleman from county durham travelled with turner as paymaster providing a frenchspeaking guide and a small coach figjoseph mallord william turner –fishermen at sea exhibited oil paint on canvassupport  x  mm frame  x  x  mmtate tpurchased tfigjoseph mallord william turnerfishermen at sea exhibited tate tjoseph mallord william turner –the post house voreppe with the grand aiguille beyond with turners cabriolet gouache and graphite on papersupport  x  mmtate daccepted by the nation as part of the turner bequest dfigjoseph mallord william turnerthe post house voreppe with the grand aiguille beyond with turners cabriolet tate djoseph mallord william turner –petworth sussex the seat of the earl of egremont dewy morning exhibited oil paint on canvassupport  x  mm frame  x  x  mmtate taccepted by hm government in lieu of tax and allocated to the tate gallery  in situ at petworth housetfigjoseph mallord william turnerpetworth sussex the seat of the earl of egremont dewy morning exhibited tate telected associate of the royal academy in  and academician in  turner was recognised as a prodigy who promised to be the outstanding painter of his generation about this time he painted his selfportrait tate n rather flattering his looks and attire to signal that he had arrived already prosperous in  he moved to a smarter address at  harley street sharing a studio with the marine painter jt serres some years his senior he took over the garden and outbuildings in  and the sole tenancy in  and in  opened a gallery on the corner of harley street and queen anne street from  his address was  queen anne street west turner’s gallery could accommodate up to about thirty works in more sympathetic conditions than in the crowded academy among early exhibits were spectacular watercolours based on drawings made during his tour in  one enthusiastic buyer of these walter fawkes became an avid collector of turner’s work also seen at the gallery were english landscapes smaller and more intimate than the pictures turner sent to the academy these attracted another collector the rd earl of egremont fawkes and mainly in later years egremont became friends as well as patrons their seats at farnley yorkshire and petworth sussex becoming homes from home for turner he stayed at farnley almost annually from  and the following year visited petworth and egremont’s cumbrian seat cockermouth castle to paint them fig his watercolours of shoots on the moors around farnley and the sparkling but bohemian gatherings at petworth vividly recall country house life and the higher social milieus in which he sometimes moved the more formal country house ‘portrait’ presenting a mansion in its parkland became a staple of his work treated with exceptional freedom and atmospherejoseph mallord william turner –tabley cheshire the seat of sir jf leicester bart calm morning exhibited oil paint on canvassupport  x  mm frame  x  x  mmtate taccepted by hm government in lieu of tax and allocated to the tate gallery  in situ at petworth housetfigjoseph mallord william turnertabley cheshire the seat of sir jf leicester bart calm morning exhibited tate tfawkes egremont and sir john leicester who was forming a gallery of modern british art split between his cheshire seat at tabley where turner also stayed in  fig and his london house were staunch admirers turner’s dominance did not go unchallenged however at the royal academy he could be bumptious pushy or rude at times trading insults with colleagues a senior academician joseph farington who had supported turner’s election summarised him in  as ‘confident presumptuous – with talent’ but came gradually to regard him with ‘puzzled incomprehension’ the academy’s president benjamin west another early advocate denounced thames views exhibited in turner’s gallery in as ‘crude blotches’ while turner and other artists associated with him were dubbed ‘white painters’ because of their use of luminous sometimes pale tones sir george beaumont a fashionable arbiter of taste was particularly hostile as aesthetically conservative as he was progressive in literary matters avidly promoting wordsworth’s poetry beaumont thought turner debased old masters like the seventeenthcentury landscape painter claude lorrain while turner resented beaumont’s enthusiasm for the young scottish painter david wilkie in  turner was upset when the prince regent did not buy a picture that he had apparently praised at an academy dinner thereby putting off other buyers who felt obliged to defer to royal interest running through the notes and drafts of verse that turner was now confiding to his sketchbooks there is a vein of bitterness at the vagaries of critics and patrons verging uncharacteristically on selfpityjoseph mallord william turner –lecture diagram  interior of the great room at somerset house london circa graphite and watercolour on papersupport  x  mmtate daccepted by the nation as part of the turner bequest dfigjoseph mallord william turnerlecture diagram  interior of the great room at somerset house london circa tate dalthough their attacks did not go away turner’s critics made little lasting impact and he grew used to and even courted controversy wary of the british institution founded in  which held rival exhibitions and in which beaumont and his friends were leading figures he exhibited there only rarely and in  in a manner evidently designed to undermine its ethos and governance despite earlier frictions he was fiercely loyal to the academy once referring to it as the ‘mother’ of artists in  he was appointed as its professor of perspective having proposed himself when the post proved hard to fill he was proud of the title sometimes adding ‘pp’ to ‘ra’ after his signature he began lecturing in  after prolonged research and preparation his poor delivery drew mixed reviews but his catholic approach to his brief ranging widely over history and theory and the illustrations he prepared for his lectures including one depicting the great room at the academy where they were delivered fig were praised he retained the post until  although he had not lectured for ten years he might have preferred to be professor of landscape a post he first suggested to the academy in  from  encouraged by an artist friend william wells he classified the history and practice of landscape art from mountainous to marine natural to ideal and his own dominance of all these aspects in a series of original prints the liber studiorum book of studies the title echoed claude’s graphic record of his work the liber veritatis and perhaps also a liber nauticus – by his former housemate serresthe lectures and the liber showed turner at his most didactic and with his gallery and other exhibited works demonstrated his extraordinary energy and determination to command the public sphere all this excluded much in the way of a private life and such as he had was closely tied to his work although it revealed a contrary need for seclusion which in later years mutated into secrecy or deliberate mystification from thamesside lodgings at sion syon ferry house isleworth – fig and upper mall hammersmith – he explored the river and pursued his favourite hobby fishing – characteristically a solitary one sketches of the thames in watercolour and oil exemplify the naturalism then emerging in british painting others transform it into an antique land inspired by claude’s classical seaports and the greek and roman literature that turner’s friend henry scott trimmer a clergyman and classicist was trying to teach him to read acutely conscious of the cultural history of the thames riverside the former home of poets and painters turner was disgusted at the demolition by a philistine baroness in  of alexander pope’s famous villa at twickenham – the subject of a picture and anguished outpourings of verse in  turner bought his own plot at twickenham where he designed and built a villa sandycombe sometimes ‘solus’ lodge fig in retreat there he was looked after by his devoted father who cooked and gardened his mother had died in  probably at bethlem and he had not married once remarking in a sketchbook that ‘woman is doubtful love’ for a few years he had been close to sarah danby the widow of a wellknown musician but inevitably they were often apart she bore two daughters evelina and georgiana who have been widely recognised as turner’s although a recent theory suggests that they were his father’s and thus his halfsisters hannah danby niece of sarah’s late husband was turner’s housekeeper at queen anne street until his deathjoseph mallord william turner –sion ferry house isleworth sunset graphite and watercolour on papersupport  x  mmtate daccepted by the nation as part of the turner bequest dfigjoseph mallord william turnersion ferry house isleworth sunset tate dwilliam havell –sandycombe lodge twickenham villa of jmw turner engraved by wb cooke published engraving on papertate ttransferred from the british museum tfigwilliam havellsandycombe lodge twickenham villa of jmw turner engraved by wb cooke published tate tjoseph mallord william turner –crossing the brook exhibited oil paint on canvassupport  x  mm frame  x  x  mmtate naccepted by the nation as part of the turner bequest nfigjoseph mallord william turnercrossing the brook exhibited tate nin  turner visited devon in glorious summer weather and encouraged by friends sketched in oil outdoors a resulting picture crossing the brook tate n fig exhibited in  weaves together the strands of private and public natural and classical in his life and art at this period the tamar valley and distant dartmoor are cast in italianate claudean terms but in turner’s distinctive colouring that his detractor beaumont called ‘peagreen insipidity’ two girls at the riverside might be evelina and georgiana with tours including visits to sussex and kent in  and another to the west country in  the  trip supplied material for picturesque views on the southern coast of england produced – by the engravers george and william bernard cooke and the publishers john murray and john and arthur arch this was the first substantial series of topographical subjects based on turner’s watercolours it was followed by surveys of rivers ports and harbours and the magisterial but unfinished picturesque views in england wales for charles heathpublished – although the last had to be abandoned as a commercial failure for many years these projects made significant contributions to his income and brought his work to a wider public as rich in memory and association as in depictions of contemporary life industry and leisure the prints reflected the nation to it itself and ensured that even today early nineteenthcentury britain is seen though turner’s eyesjoseph mallord william turner –the field of waterloo exhibited oil paint on canvassupport  x  mmtate naccepted by the nation as part of the turner bequest nfigjoseph mallord william turnerthe field of waterloo exhibited tate nin  turner visited holland and belgium to see the battlefield of waterloo and the rhineland his picture the field of waterloo exhibited in  tate n fig was modern humane in its mingling of the dead of all sides and accompanied by an epigraph from the famous ‘waterloo stanzas’ in byron’s recentlypublished poem childe harold’s pilgrimage as a reflection of recent events it stood in total contrast to pictures of the rise and fall of ancient carthage – his greatest claudean works exhibited in  and  – that allegorised the collapse of napoleon in historical terms fig a set of fifty rhine views in watercolour and gouache was bought by fawkes who in  and  exhibited his collection now numbering some seventy turners at his london house also in  sir john leicester opened his town house to the public with other important turners on the walls these shows where turner mingled in the crowd of visitors and others of his watercolours held by publishers and engravers in succeeding decades placed him at the heart of the diversifying exhibition culture of the time they complemented his exhibits at the academy and turner’s gallery where distinguished visitors included in  the italian sculptor antonio canova who pronounced turner a great genius following a period of closure for improvements the gallery reopened in  thereafter evolving from a showcase of new work into a museum fig housing a representative collection from which the artist was reluctant to part or to which he added when possible by buying back pictures – for example at the sale of lord de tabley the former sir john leicester in  turner’s plans for his legacy including a gallery of his pictures at the new national gallery or attached to almshouses on his land at twickenham became a preoccupation in later yearsjoseph mallord william turner –the decline of the carthaginian empire  exhibited oil paint on canvassupport  x  mm frame  x  x mmtate naccepted by the nation as part of the turner bequest nfigjoseph mallord william turnerthe decline of the carthaginian empire  exhibited tate ngeorge jones interior of turners gallery the artist showing his works coil on millboard x  mm ashmolean museum university of oxfordfiggeorge jonesinterior of turners gallery the artist showing his works cashmolean museum university of oxfordjohn doyle –samuel rogers at his breakfast table engraved by charles mottram cengraving and mezzotint on paperimage  x  mmtate tpresented by dr david blayney brown tfigjohn doylesamuel rogers at his breakfast table engraved by charles mottram ctate tin  and  turner visited italy the first time he travelled to venice rome and naples but on his second visit based himself in rome where he painted and exhibited new works his bright colouring and impromptu handling bemused german artists who expected more finish in the intervening years turner continued his routine of touring painting and working for publishers at home and on the continent on successive visits to france he explored the loire in  and seine from – a larger plan to portray the great rivers of europe was never realised but three volumes of prints were published by heath with letterpress by leitch ritchie as wandering by the loire and seine – marketed as ‘turner’s annual tour’ and later combined as rivers of francethey were pitched at new middle class readers who might expect to follow in the artist’s footsteps meanwhile in  turner had opened a seam of overtly literary topography visiting scotland to illustrate walter scott’s picturesque antiquities illustrations to scott’s poetry novels and life of napoleon byron the bankerpoet samuel rogers thomas campbell and thomas moore as well as john milton and the bible often designed as vignettes – a form turner made very much his own – followed in the coming years among living poets turner was fondest of byron’s writing borrowing more passages from childe harold as themes for pictures but he knew rogers and scott best with other luminaries of literary and artistic london he was pictured among the guests who frequented rogers’s celebrated breakfastparties in st james’s fig he visited scott at abbotsford and scott’s role as stagemanager of george iv’s visit to edinburgh in  was a factor in his attempt at a set of paintings recording the royal progress these were left unfinished but in  turner finally obtained a longedfor royal commission an immense picture of the battle of trafalgar national maritime museum greenwichin  fawkes died turner never revisited farnley but in the decade until egremont’s death in  he had the run of petworth where he used the old library as a studio from contemporary accounts and on the evidence of turner’s many drawings figs and  it was a special place its treasures and varied company at his behest egremont’s unconventional household of rival mistresses swarms of children and visiting artists would in due course arouse victorian censure but gave turner a grand extended family the more welcome after his father died in september joseph mallord william turner –the artist and his admirers watercolour and bodycolour on papersupport  x  mmtate daccepted by the nation as part of the turner bequest dfigjoseph mallord william turnerthe artist and his admirers tate djoseph mallord william turner –petworth the white library looking down the en